{
  "texts": [
    "The following subsections provide a detailed analysis of LVRT and SSR.",
    "Low voltage ride through of DFIG-based WECSLVRT is crucial for DFIG wind turbines to remain connected to the grid during voltage fluctuations, preventing the turbine from being disconnected and enhancing grid stability [6,21].",
    "LVRT techniques allow DFIG wind turbines to stay connected to the supply system even during faults or severe voltage dips, while maintaining control of active and reactive power during the event [22].",
    "Among the LVRT methods, the most widely used is crowbar protection, which essentially short-circuits the rotor-side converter for a short period, preventing overvoltage and overcurrent.",
    "However, while this technique is effective, it can result in a loss of power control during fault conditions [23,24].To address these challenges, advanced LVRT strategies have been developed."
  ]
}